                        Animosi legati libera, et cordata apophtegmata. Qualis posteà legatus Popilius: orator verbo, factoq[ue] peremptorius. i[nfr]a, 813. 
                        Duo eximia pro legato exempla: sed urbaniùs exercenda. Credo, inter arcana nostrorum legatoru[m], Smithi, Vuttoni, Vilsonis, 
                        Dali: quatuor iuris Doctoru[m]. Sed quid abijcio tempus scripturiendo? De talibus viderit doctor Gentilis in libris de Legationib. 
                        et de iure belli. Redeo ad ipsum hîc Archetypum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Gaius Popillius Laenas"/>
                    <person name="Thomas Smith"/>
                    <person name="Edward Wotton"/>
                    <person name="Thomas Wilson"/>
                    <person name="Valentine Dale"/>
                    <person name="Alberico Gentili"/>
                    <book title="De Legationibus Libri Tres"/>
                    <book title="De iure belli libri tres"/>
                    <internal_ref>
                        <target ref="PrincetonPA6452:00000835" text="813"/>
                    </internal_ref>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The outspoken and judicious apophtegms of a bold ambassador. Such as later ambassador Popilius: 
                a decisive orator in word and deed, [see] below 813. Two excellent examples for an ambassador, but in private settings, 
                I belief, one should follow, in a more sophisticated style, those of our ambassadors Smith, Wotton, Wilson, and Dale, four doctors of law. 
                But why do I waste my time by desiring to write? Doctor Gentili attends to these things in his books De legationibus and De iure belli. 
                I return to the original text here.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
